"v.用指轻弹；蹦跳；a.无礼的 【考】 flip : respect / nonchalant : concern(不敬的无尊敬/不关 心的无关心) adj. 鲁莽的, 轻率的(不经意的失礼的) 【记】fl = fly飞, lip(n 嘴唇): 总是对小姑娘飞吻－鲁莽的, 轻率的 【类】flip: respect = nonchalant: concern鲁莽的没有尊敬 = 不关心的没有关心 【记】音:飞 + lip 嘴唇→飞吻→不敬；音：非礼 flip (v.)  1590s (1520s in flip-flop), imitative or else a contraction of fillip (q.v.), which also is held to be imitative. Sense of ""get excited"" is first recorded 1950; flip one's lid ""lose one's head, go wild"" is from 1950. For flip (adj.) ""glib,"" see flippant. Meaning ""to flip a coin"" (to decide something) is by 1879. As a noun by 1690s. Related: Flipped. Flipping (adj.) as euphemism for fucking is British slang first recorded 1911 in D.H. Lawrence. Flip side (of a gramophone record) is by 1949. flip (n.)  sailors' hot drink usually containing beer, brandy and sugar, 1690s, from flip (v.); so called from notion of it being ""whipped up"" or beaten."
